The most likely cause of your issues is the fact that your file resources are still &quot;open&quot;.  You should make sure they are closed before you try deleting or renaming the files.

I would strongly recommend making use [The try-with-resources Statement](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/exceptions/tryResourceClose.html) as this will take a lot of pain and additional &quot;boiler plate&quot; code out of the picture.

I would also check the return states of `File#delete` and `File#renameTo` to determine if those operations were successful or not and take appropriate action if they&#39;re not.

For example, you might be able to do something more like...

    try {
        try (PrintWriter pw = new PrintWriter(new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter(tempFile, true))); BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(filePath))) {
            while ((currentLine = br.readLine()) != null) {
                line++;
                if (deleteLine != line) {
                    pw.println(currentLine);
                }
            }
        }
        File oldFile = new File(filePath);
        File newFile = new File(tempFile);

        if (!oldFile.exists()) {
            throw new IOException(&quot;Could not find old file &quot; + oldFile);
        }
        if (!oldFile.delete()) {
            throw new IOException(&quot;Could not remove old file &quot; + oldFile);
        }
        File dump = new File(filePath);
        if (!newFile.renameTo(dump)) {
            throw new IOException(&quot;Could not rename&quot; + newFile + &quot; to &quot; + dump);
